# Frontend Rule — UI and DX Standards

The product must feel structured, professional, and builder-oriented.

## Frontend priorities
- clarity over visual complexity
- strong information architecture
- fast navigation between projects, agents, apps, deployments
- schema-driven forms where practical
- deployment state always visible

## Main UX entities
- organization
- project
- environment
- agent
- app
- deployment
- route
- secret
- template

## UI requirements
- form validation must be user-friendly
- destructive actions must require confirmation
- loading and empty states must be explicit
- error states must be actionable
- logs/status should be readable and filterable

## Code standards
- use TypeScript strictly
- prefer reusable components from shared ui package
- avoid business logic in presentation components
- colocate component tests when useful
- use server-state patterns consistently

## Forbidden patterns
- giant page components with mixed business logic
- direct fetch calls scattered across UI
- duplicated form schemas
- inconsistent naming between backend and frontend models
